&lt;p>&lt;strong>From Consciousness to Cosmos: Fields, Particles, Matter, and the Emergence of Size&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 class="relative group">Introduction: From Objects to Fields
&lt;div id="introduction-from-objects-to-fields" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#introduction-from-objects-to-fields" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>In everyday life, we experience the world as objects.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>A stone has weight.
A mango has color, taste, smell, and shape.
A human body has size, temperature, movement, and life.
A planet has mass, orbit, and gravity.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Zero, Point, Śūnya, and the Many Faces of Nothing</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/zero-point-shunya-nothingness/</link><pubDate>Fri, 12 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/zero-point-shunya-nothingness/</guid><description>&lt;p>
&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5308-zero-point-shunya-nothingness.jpg" alt="Zero, Point, Śūnya, and the Many Faces of Nothing" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Almost ten years later, I reflect here again on Śūnya and Zero — revisiting the question from the &lt;a href="https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/about-shoonya-zero/">2016 article&lt;/a>.&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">Zero, Point, Śūnya, Nothingness, Emptiness, Vacuum, Abhāva and Absence
&lt;div id="zero-point-%C5%9B%C5%ABnya-nothingness-emptiness-vacuum-abh%C4%81va-and-absence" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#zero-point-%C5%9B%C5%ABnya-nothingness-emptiness-vacuum-abh%C4%81va-and-absence" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;h2 class="relative group">A Philosophical Inquiry into the Many Faces of “Nothing”
&lt;div id="a-philosophical-inquiry-into-the-many-faces-of-nothing" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#a-philosophical-inquiry-into-the-many-faces-of-nothing" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>Human beings live among things. We see bodies, trees, rivers, stars, houses, tools, people, emotions, events, and memories. Our language is built around objects. Our survival depends on recognizing objects: food, danger, shelter, friend, enemy, boundary, distance, ownership, loss, gain.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Advaita Vedanta and Hans Peter Durr</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/vedanta-and-hans-peter-durr/</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Oct 2024 08:33:00 +0530</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/vedanta-and-hans-peter-durr/</guid><description>&lt;p>
&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5272-Vedanta-and-Hans-Peter-Durr.jpg" alt="Advaita Vedanta and Hans Peter Durr" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">Advaita Vedanta and Hans Peter Durr
&lt;div id="advaita-vedanta-and-hans-peter-durr" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#advaita-vedanta-and-hans-peter-durr" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>Hans-Peter Dürr (7 October 1929 – 18 May 2014), a renowned German physicist, had deep insights into the philosophical parallels between modern physics and ancient spiritual wisdom, particularly Vedanta. While Dürr did not explicitly write a comprehensive work focused solely on Vedanta, in his numerous interviews, lectures, and writings, he often discussed how the findings of quantum physics aligned with many ideas found in Vedanta and other Eastern philosophies.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Learning Process</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/learning-process/</link><pubDate>Wed, 21 Apr 2021 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/learning-process/</guid><description>&lt;p>
&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5152-Learning-Process.jpg" alt="Learning Process" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">Learning Process
&lt;div id="learning-process" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#learning-process" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>When you see some long physics or maths formula then don’t get scared of it. It is just a way to represent the reality. Is it an absolute reality? No, it just represents that reality, and the absolute reality is very close to this. Whether it is a formula of gravity or force or angular momentum or energy calculations or anything else.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>